# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-solr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Lucene has been ported to other programming languages including Object Pascal, Perl, C#, C++, Python, Ruby and PHP.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Doug Cutting originally wrote Lucene in 1999.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] He had previously written two while at Xerox PARC, one at Apple, and a fourth at Excite.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] It was initially available for download from its home at the SourceForge web site.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] It joined the Apache Software Foundation's Jakarta family of open-source Java products in September 2001 and became its own top-level Apache project in February 2005.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] The name Lucene is Doug Cutting's wife's middle name and her maternal grandmother's first name.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Lucene formerly included a number of sub-projects, such as Lucene.NET, Mahout, Tika and Nutch.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] These three are now independent top-level projects.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] In March 2010, the Apache Solr search server joined as a Lucene sub-project, merging the developer communities.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Version 4.0 was released on October 12, 2012.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] In March 2021, Lucene changed its logo, and Apache Solr became a top level Apache project again, independent from Lucene.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] While suitable for any application that requires full text indexing and searching capability, Lucene is recognized for its utility in the implementation of Internet search engines and local, single-site searching.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Lucene includes a feature to perform a fuzzy search based on edit distance.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Lucene has also been used to implement recommendation systems.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] For example, Lucene's 'MoreLikeThis' Class can generate recommendations for similar documents.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] In contrast, citation-based document similarity measures tended to be more suitable for recommending more broadly related documents, meaning citation-based approaches may be more suitable for generating serendipitous recommendations, as long as documents to be recommended contain in-text citations.
[src:apache-solr/apache-lucene] Lucene itself is just an indexing and search library and does not contain crawling and HTML parsing functionality.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr runs as a standalone full-text search server.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] It uses the Lucene Java search library at its core for full-text indexing and search, and has REST-like HTTP/XML and JSON APIs that make it usable from most popular programming languages.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr's external configuration allows it to be tailored to many types of applications without Java coding, and it has a plugin architecture to support more advanced customization.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Apache Solr is developed in an open, collaborative manner by the Apache Solr project at the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In 2004, Solr was created by Yonik Seeley at CNET Networks as an in-house project to add search capability for the company website.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In January 2006, CNET Networks decided to openly publish the source code by donating it to the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Like any new Apache project, it entered an incubation period that helped solve organizational, legal, and financial issues.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In January 2007, Solr graduated from incubation status into a standalone top-level project (TLP) and grew steadily with accumulated features, thereby attracting users, contributors, and committers.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Although quite new as a public project, it powered several high-traffic websites.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In September 2008, Solr 1.3 was released including distributed search capabilities and performance enhancements among many others.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In January 2009, Yonik Seeley along with Grant Ingersoll and Erik Hatcher joined Lucidworks (formerly Lucid Imagination), the first company providing commercial support and training for Apache Solr search technologies.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Since then, support offerings around Solr have been abundant.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In November 2009, saw the release of Solr 1.4.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] This version introduced enhancements in indexing, searching and faceting along with many other improvements such as rich document processing (PDF, Word, HTML), Search Results clustering based on Carrot2 and also improved database integration.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] The release also features many additional plug-ins.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In March 2010, the Lucene and Solr projects merged.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Separate downloads continued, but the products were now jointly developed by a single set of committers.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In 2011, the Solr version number scheme was changed in order to match that of Lucene.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] After Solr 1.4, the next release of Solr was labeled 3.1, in order to keep Solr and Lucene on the same version number.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In October 2012, Solr version 4.0 was released, including the new SolrCloud feature.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] 2013 and 2014 saw a number of Solr releases in the 4.x line, steadily growing the feature set and improving reliability.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In February 2015, Solr 5.0 was released, the first release where Solr is packaged as a standalone application, ending official support for deploying Solr as a war.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr 5.3 featured a built-in pluggable Authentication and Authorization framework.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Added support for executing Parallel SQL queries across SolrCloud collections.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Includes StreamExpression support and a new JDBC Driver for the SQL Interface.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In September 2017, Solr 7.0 was released.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] This release among other things, added support multiple replica types, auto-scaling, and a Math engine.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In March 2019, Solr 8.0 was released including many bugfixes and component updates.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr nodes can now listen and serve HTTP/2 requests.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Be aware that by default, internal requests are also sent by using HTTP/2.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Furthermore, an admin UI login was added with support for BasicAuth and Kerberos.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] And plotting math expressions in Apache Zeppelin is now possible.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In November 2020, Bloomberg donated the Solr Operator to the Lucene/Solr project.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] The Solr Operator helps deploy and run Solr in Kubernetes.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In February 2021, Solr was established as a separate Apache project (TLP), independent from Lucene.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] In May 2022, Solr 9.0 was released, as the first release independent from Lucene, requiring Java 11, and with highlights such as KNN "Neural" search, better modularization, more security plugins and more.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Querying: understanding the terms of a query asked by the user.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] These terms can be images or keywords, for example.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Mapping: Solr maps the user query to the documents stored in the database to find the appropriate result.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Ranking: as soon as the engine searches the indexed documents, it ranks the outputs by their relevance.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr has both individuals and companies who contribute new features and bug fixes.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr is bundled as the built-in search in many applications such as content management systems and enterprise content management systems.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Hadoop distributions from Cloudera, Hortonworks and MapR all bundle Solr as the search engine for their products marketed for big data.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] DataStax DSE integrates Solr as a search engine with Cassandra.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr is supported as an end point in various data processing frameworks and Enterprise integration frameworks.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] Solr exposes industry standard HTTP REST-like APIs with both XML and JSON support, and will integrate with any system or programming language supporting these standards.
[src:apache-solr/apache-solr] For ease of use there are also client libraries available for Java, C#, PHP, Python, Ruby and most other popular programming languages.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] In text retrieval, **full-text search** refers to a set of techniques for searching a single computer-stored document or a collection in a full-text database.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Full-text search is distinguished from searches based on metadata or on specific parts of documents, such as titles, abstracts, selected sections, or bibliographical references.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] In a full-text search, a search engine examines the words in stored documents to find matches for user queries.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Full-text-search techniques began to appear in the 1960s (for example, IBM STAIRS in 1969), and became common in online bibliographic databases during the 1990s.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Many websites and application programs, including word processors, implement full-text search functionality.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Some web search engines, such as the former AltaVista, indexed the full text of web pages, while others indexed only selected portions of pages.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] When dealing with a small number of documents, a full-text-search engine can scan the contents of each document directly for every query, a strategy known as "serial scanning." Some tools, such as grep, operate in this way.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] When the number of documents or queries is large, full-text search is typically divided into two tasks: indexing and searching.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] During indexing, the engine scans all documents and builds a list of search terms, often called an index, or more precisely, a concordance.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] During the search stage, queries are performed against the index rather than the original documents.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The indexer records each term found in a document and may note its position within the text.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Common words, known as stop words (for instance, "the" or "and"), are omitted because they add little value to search results.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The diagram at the right illustrates a search with low recall and low precision.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] In the diagram, red and green dots represent the total population of potential search results for a given query, with green dots indicating relevant results and red indicating irrelevant results.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Relevance is indicated by proximity to the center of the inner circle.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The results actually returned by the search are highlighted on a light-blue background.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] In the example, only one relevant result of three possible relevant results was returned, giving a recall of ⅓ (33%).
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The precision is 1/4 (25%), since only one of the four results returned was relevant.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Due to the ambiguities of natural language, full-text-search systems typically include features such as filtering to increase precision and stemming to increase recall.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Controlled-vocabulary search can also help alleviate low-precision results by tagging documents to reduce ambiguity.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] There is generally a trade-off between precision and recall: increasing precision can reduce overall recall, while increasing recall may lower precision.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Full-text search can retrieve many documents that are not relevant to the intended query.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Such documents are called **false positives** (see Type I error).
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The retrieval of irrelevant documents is often caused by the inherent ambiguity of natural language.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] In the accompanying diagram, false positives are represented by irrelevant results (red dots) that were returned by the search (highlighted on a light-blue background).
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] At a basic level, search engines return items that contain the exact phrase listed in the query.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Tools and methodologies exist to account for grammatical or typographical errors and to refine results; however, these techniques still typically require a close textual match.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Because there are often multiple ways to refer to an entity or concept, full-text search may fail to retrieve an item if the exact term is not used in the query.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Not to be confused with semantic search, synonyms can be retrieved by creating an index of related terms, such that when a variation of a word is searched, items containing any of the related terms may also be returned.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The limitations of full-text searching have been addressed in two ways: by providing users with tools to express search questions more precisely, and by developing algorithms that improve retrieval precision.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] The following is a partial list of software products that support full-text indexing and search.
[src:apache-solr/full-text-search] Some of these are accompanied by documentation describing their architecture or algorithms, which may provide additional insight into how full-text search is implemented.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Update handlers are request handlers designed to add, delete and update documents to the index.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] In addition to having plugins for importing rich documents (see Indexing with Solr Cell and Apache Tika), Solr natively supports indexing structured documents in XML, CSV, and JSON.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The recommended way to configure and use request handlers is with path based names that map to paths in the request URL.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] However, request handlers can also be specified with the `qt` (query type) parameter if the `requestDispatcher` is appropriately configured.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] It is possible to access the same handler using more than one name, which can be useful if you wish to specify different sets of default options.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] A single unified update request handler supports XML, CSV, JSON, and javabin update requests, delegating to the appropriate `ContentStreamLoader` based on the `Content-Type` of the ContentStream.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If you need to pre-process documents after they are loaded but before they are indexed (or even checked against the schema), Solr has document preprocessing plugins for Update Request Handlers, called Update Request Processors, which allow for default and custom configuration chains.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The default configuration file has the update request handler configured by default.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Index update commands can be sent as XML message to the update handler using `Content-type: application/xml` or `Content-type: text/xml`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The add command supports some optional attributes which may be specified.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Add the document within the specified number of milliseconds.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Indicates if the unique key constraints should be checked to overwrite previous versions of the same document (see below).
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If the document schema defines a unique key, then by default an `/update` operation to add a document will overwrite (i.e., replace) any document in the index with the same unique key.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If no unique key has been defined, indexing performance is somewhat faster, as no check has to be made for an existing documents to replace.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If you have a unique key field, but you feel confident that you can safely bypass the uniqueness check (e.g., you build your indexes in batch, and your indexing code guarantees it never adds the same document more than once) you can specify the `overwrite="false"` option when adding your documents.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The `<commit>` operation writes all documents loaded since the last commit to one or more segment files on the disk.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Before a commit has been issued, newly indexed content is not visible to searches.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The commit operation opens a new searcher, and triggers any event listeners that have been configured.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Commits may be issued explicitly with a `<commit/>` message, and can also be triggered from `<autocommit>` parameters in `solrconfig.xml`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The `<optimize>` operation requests Solr to merge internal data structures.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] For a large index, optimization will take some time to complete, but by merging many small segment files into larger segments, search performance may improve.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If you are using Solr’s replication mechanism to distribute searches across many systems, be aware that after an optimize, a complete index will need to be transferred.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Blocks until a new searcher is opened and registered as the main query searcher, making the changes visible.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Merges segments that have more than 10% deleted docs, expunging the deleted documents in the process.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Resulting segments will respect `maxMergedSegmentMB`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This option only applies in a `<commit> operation`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Makes a best effort attempt to merge the segments down to no more than this number of segments but does not guarantee that the goal will be achieved.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Unless there is tangible evidence that optimizing to a small number of segments is beneficial, this parameter should be omitted and the default behavior accepted.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This option only applies in a `<optimize` operation.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Default is unlimited, resulting segments respect the `maxMergedSegmentMB` setting.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Documents can be deleted from the index in two ways.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] "Delete by ID" deletes the document with the specified ID, and can be used only if a UniqueID field has been defined in the schema.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] "Delete by Query" deletes all documents matching a specified query, although `commitWithin` is ignored for a Delete by Query.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] A single delete message can contain multiple delete operations.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The rollback command rolls back all add and deletes made to the index since the last commit.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] It neither calls any event listeners nor creates a new searcher.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] You can post several commands in a single XML file by grouping them with the surrounding `<update>` element.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] You can use the `curl` utility to perform any of the above commands, using its `--data-binary` option to append the XML message to the `curl` command, and generating a HTTP POST request.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The approach above works well, but using the `--data-binary` option causes `curl` to load the whole `myfile.xml` into memory before posting it to server.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This may be problematic when dealing with multi-gigabyte files.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The status field will be non-zero in case of failure.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The Scripting module provides a separate XSLT Update Request Handler that allows you to index any arbitrary XML by using the `<tr>` parameter to apply an XSL transformation.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] You must have an XSLT stylesheet in the `conf/xslt` directory of your configset that can transform the incoming data to the expected `<add><doc/></add>` format, and use the `tr` parameter to specify the name of that stylesheet.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] You will need to enable the scripting Module before using this feature.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The XSLT Update Request Handler accepts the `tr` parameter, which identifies the XML transformation to use.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The transformation must be found in the Solr `conf/xslt` directory.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The example below, from the `sample_techproducts_configs` configset in the Solr distribution, shows how the XSLT Update Request Handler is configured.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] A value of 5 for `xsltCacheLifetimeSeconds` is good for development, to see XSLT changes quickly.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] For production you probably want a much higher value.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This stylesheet transforms Solr’s XML search result format into Solr’s Update XML syntax.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Solr can accept JSON that conforms to a defined structure, or can accept arbitrary JSON-formatted documents.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If sending arbitrarily formatted JSON, there are some additional parameters that need to be sent with the update request, described in the section Transforming and Indexing Custom JSON.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] JSON formatted update requests may be sent to Solr’s `/update` handler using `Content-Type: application/json` or `Content-Type: text/json`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] In general, the JSON update syntax supports all of the update commands that the XML update handler supports, through a straightforward mapping.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] As with other update handlers, parameters such as `commit`, `commitWithin`, `optimize`, and `overwrite` may be specified in the URL instead of in the body of the message.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The JSON update format allows for a simple delete-by-id.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The value of a `delete` can be an array which contains a list of zero or more specific document id’s (not a range) to be deleted.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Note: Delete-by-id doesn’t work for child/nested docs.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] You can specify the version of deletes in the body of the update request as well.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This is covered in the section Transforming and Indexing Custom JSON.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] CSV formatted update requests may be sent to Solr’s `/update` handler using `Content-Type: application/csv` or `Content-Type: text/csv`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The CSV handler allows the specification of many parameters in the URL in the form: `f.*parameter*.*optional_fieldname*=*value*`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The table below describes the parameters for the update handler.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This parameter is global; for per-field usage, see the `split` parameter.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If `true`, remove leading and trailing whitespace from values.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This parameter can be either global or per-field.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Set to `true` if first line of input contains field names.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] These will be used if the `fieldnames` parameter is absent.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Comma-separated list of field names to use when adding documents.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] A literal value for a specified field name.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Comma separated list of field names to skip.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Number of lines to discard in the input stream before the CSV data starts, including the header, if present.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The character optionally used to surround values to preserve characters such as the CSV separator or whitespace.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This standard CSV format handles the encapsulator itself appearing in an encapsulated value by doubling the encapsulator.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This parameter is global; for per-field usage, see `split`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The character used for escaping CSV separators or other reserved character.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If an escape is specified, the encapsulator is not used unless also explicitly specified since most formats use either encapsulation or escaping, not both.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Keep and index zero length (empty) fields.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This parameter can be global or per-field.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Format is `map=value:replacement` (which can be empty).
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If `true`, split a field into multiple values by a separate parser.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This parameter is used on a per-field basis, for example `f.FIELD_NAME_GOES_HERE.split=true`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If `true`, check for and overwrite duplicate documents, based on the uniqueKey field declared in the Solr schema.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] If you know the documents you are indexing do not contain any duplicates then you may see a considerable speed up setting this to `false`.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Issues a commit after the data has been ingested.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Map the `rowid` (line number) to a field specified by the value of the parameter, for instance if your CSV doesn’t have a unique key and you want to use the row id as such.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] Add the given offset (as an integer) to the `rowid` before adding it to the document.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The same feature used to index CSV documents can also be easily used to index tab-delimited files (TSV files) and even handle backslash escaping rather than CSV encapsulation.
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] This file could then be imported into Solr by setting the `separator` to tab (%09) and the `escape` to backslash (%5c).
[src:apache-solr/indexing-with-update-handlers] The `/update/csv` path may be useful for clients sending in CSV formatted update commands from applications where setting the Content-Type proves difficult.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] ApacheTM Solr is a search server built on top of Apache LuceneTM, an open source, Java-based, information retrieval library.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Solr is designed to drive powerful document retrieval or analytical applications involving unstructured data, semi-structured data or a mix of unstructured and structured data.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] It also has secondary support for limited relational, graph, statistical, data analysis or storage related use cases.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Since Solr is Apache 2.0 licensed open source software designed for extensibility, it gives you the freedom to adapt or optimize it for almost any commercial or non-commercial use case.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Solr’s query syntax and parsers offer support for everything from the simplest keyword searching through to complex queries on multiple fields and faceted search results.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Collapsing and clustering results offer compelling features for e-commerce and storefronts.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Streaming expressions allow you to conduct analytics on an entire corpus, a subset matching a query, or a random sample from a set of documents.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Powerful math expressions build on streaming expressions to provide the backbone for advanced analysis and predictive analytics use cases.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Advanced relevancy tuning is also supported; Solr provides access to almost all of Lucene’s text analysis features including tokenization, stemming, synonyms and much more, allowing you to tune relevancy based on knowledge of your users and your domain.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Solr even allows for customization of relevancy via machine learning using the Learning To Rank feature.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Queries are transmitted to Solr via HTTP 1.1 or 2.0 requests and the response is typically a list of structured document descriptors.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] In the classic example, 10 descriptors are returned, each including a URL to locate the document (often rendered as "10 blue links").
[src:apache-solr/introduction] However, Solr can go far beyond document locators and many other types of document metadata might also be included.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Flexible schema configurations allow nearly any type of metadata to be associated with a document indexed in Solr.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] The schema elements page of the indexing guide has more details on these options.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] JSON is the default response format, but it could also be XML, CSV, optimized binary, or (with customization) any format you desire.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] This means that a wide variety of clients will be able to use Solr.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Such clients might be web applications, browsers, rich client applications, or mobile devices.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Any platform capable of HTTP can talk to Solr.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Several Client APIs are provided for use in common programming languages.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] In addition to providing a network accessible engine for Lucene based document retrieval, Solr provides the ability to scale beyond the limitations of a single machine.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Indexes can be sharded and replicated for performance and reliability, using either one of two Solr Cluster Types.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] The most scalable option uses Apache ZookeeperTM to coordinate management activities across the cluster.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] The older approach requires no supporting infrastructure, however instances are managed directly by administrators.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] Solr scaling and high availability features are so effective that some of the largest and most famous internet sites use Solr.
[src:apache-solr/introduction] A partial, typically self nominated, list of sites using Solr can be found at https://solr.apache.org/community.html#powered-by.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Popular search engines focus on the full-text indexing of online, natural language documents.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Media types such as pictures, video, audio, and graphics are also searchable.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Meta search engines reuse the indices of other services and do not store a local index whereas cache-based search engines permanently store the index along with the corpus.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Unlike full-text indices, partial-text services restrict the depth indexed to reduce index size.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Larger services typically perform indexing at a predetermined time interval due to the required time and processing costs, while agent-based search engines index in real time.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The purpose of storing an index is to optimize speed and performance in finding relevant documents for a search query.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Without an index, the search engine would scan every document in the corpus, which would require considerable time and computing power.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For example, while an index of 10,000 documents can be queried within milliseconds, a sequential scan of every word in 10,000 large documents could take hours.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The additional computer storage required to store the index, as well as the considerable increase in the time required for an update to take place, are traded off for the time saved during information retrieval.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] How data enters the index, or how words or subject features are added to the index during text corpus traversal, and whether multiple indexers can work asynchronously.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The indexer must first check whether it is updating old content or adding new content.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] , that is, whether information should be data compressed or filtered.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The speed of finding an entry in a data structure, compared with how quickly it can be updated or removed, is a central focus of computer science.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] How important it is for the service to be reliable.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Search engine architectures vary in the way indexing is performed and in methods of index storage to meet the various design factors.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Figuratively structured like a tree, supports linear time lookup.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] , which is important for search engine indexing.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] A major drawback is that storing a word in the tree may require space beyond that required to store the word itself.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] A major challenge in the design of search engines is the management of serial computing processes.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] There are many opportunities for race conditions and coherent faults.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For example, a new document is added to the corpus and the index must be updated, but the index simultaneously needs to continue responding to search queries.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] This is a collision between two competing tasks.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Consider that authors are producers of information, and a web crawler is the consumer of this information, grabbing the text and storing it in a cache (or corpus).
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is the consumer of the information produced by the corpus, and the inverted index is the consumer of information produced by the forward index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] This is commonly referred to as a **producer-consumer model**.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The indexer is the producer of searchable information and users are the consumers that need to search.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The challenge is magnified when working with distributed storage and distributed processing.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In an effort to scale with larger amounts of indexed information, the search engine's architecture may involve distributed computing, where the search engine consists of several machines operating in unison.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] This increases the possibilities for incoherency and makes it more difficult to maintain a fully synchronized, distributed, parallel architecture.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines incorporate an inverted index when evaluating a search query to quickly locate documents containing the words in a query and then rank these documents by relevance.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Because the inverted index stores a list of the documents containing each word, the search engine can use direct access to find the documents associated with each word in the query in order to retrieve the matching documents quickly.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] This index can only determine whether a word exists within a particular document, since it stores no information regarding the frequency and position of the word; it is therefore considered to be a Boolean index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Such an index determines which documents match a query but does not rank matched documents.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In some designs the index includes additional information such as the frequency of each word in each document or the positions of a word in each document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Position information enables the search algorithm to identify word proximity to support searching for phrases; frequency can be used to help in ranking the relevance of documents to the query.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Such topics are the central research focus of information retrieval.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is a sparse matrix, since not all words are present in each document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] To reduce computer storage memory requirements, it is stored differently from a two dimensional array.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The index is similar to the term document matrices employed by latent semantic analysis.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index can be considered a form of a hash table.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In some cases the index is a form of a binary tree, which requires additional storage but may reduce the lookup time.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In larger indices the architecture is typically a distributed hash table.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For phrase searching, a specialized form of an inverted index called a positional index is used.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] A positional index not only stores the ID of the document containing the token but also the exact position(s) of the token within the document in the postings list.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The occurrences of the phrase specified in the query are retrieved by navigating these postings list and identifying the indexes at which the desired terms occur in the expected order (the same as the order in the phrase).
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Check that this occurrence is immediately after the occurrence of "first".
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If not, continue to the next occurrence of "first".
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The postings lists can be navigated using a binary search in order to minimize the time complexity of this procedure.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is filled via a merge or rebuild.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] A rebuild is similar to a merge but first deletes the contents of the inverted index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The architecture may be designed to support incremental indexing, where a merge identifies the document or documents to be added or updated and then parses each document into words.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For technical accuracy, a merge conflates newly indexed documents, typically residing in virtual memory, with the index cache residing on one or more computer hard drives.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] After parsing, the indexer adds the referenced document to the document list for the appropriate words.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The inverted index is so named because it is an inversion of the forward index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The forward index stores a list of words for each document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The rationale behind developing a forward index is that as documents are parsed, it is better to intermediately store the words per document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The delineation enables asynchronous system processing, which partially circumvents the inverted index update bottleneck.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is sorted to transform it to an inverted index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The forward index is essentially a list of pairs consisting of a document and a word, collated by the document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Converting the forward index to an inverted index is only a matter of sorting the pairs by the words.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In this regard, the inverted index is a word-sorted forward index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Generating or maintaining a large-scale search engine index represents a significant storage and processing challenge.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines utilize a form of compression to reduce the size of the indices on disk.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Consider the following scenario for a full text, Internet search engine.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Given this scenario, an uncompressed index (assuming a non-conflated, simple, index) for 2 billion web pages would need to store 500 billion word entries.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] At 1 byte per character, or 5 bytes per word, this would require 2500 gigabytes of storage space alone.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] This space requirement may be even larger for a fault-tolerant distributed storage architecture.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Depending on the compression technique chosen, the index can be reduced to a fraction of this size.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The tradeoff is the time and processing power required to perform compression and decompression.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Notably, large scale search engine designs incorporate the cost of storage as well as the costs of electricity to power the storage.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Document parsing breaks apart the components (words) of a document or other form of media for insertion into the forward and inverted indices.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The words found are called *tokens*, and so, in the context of search engine indexing and natural language processing, parsing is more commonly referred to as tokenization.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] It is also sometimes called word boundary disambiguation, tagging, text segmentation, content analysis, text analysis, text mining, concordance generation, speech segmentation, lexing, or lexical analysis.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The terms 'indexing', 'parsing', and 'tokenization' are used interchangeably in corporate slang.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Natural language processing is the subject of continuous research and technological improvement.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Tokenization presents many challenges in extracting the necessary information from documents for indexing to support quality searching.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Tokenization for indexing involves multiple technologies, the implementation of which are commonly kept as corporate secrets.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The goal during tokenization is to identify words for which users will search.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Language-specific logic is employed to properly identify the boundaries of words, which is often the rationale for designing a parser for each language supported (or for groups of languages with similar boundary markers and syntax).
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] These techniques are language-dependent, as the syntax varies among languages.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Documents do not always clearly identify the language of the document or represent it accurately.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In tokenizing the document, some search engines attempt to automatically identify the language of the document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In order to correctly identify which bytes of a document represent characters, the file format must be correctly handled.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Search engines that support multiple file formats must be able to correctly open and access the document and be able to tokenize the characters of the document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The quality of the natural language data may not always be perfect.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] An unspecified number of documents, particularly on the Internet, do not closely obey proper file protocol.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] characters may be mistakenly encoded into various parts of a document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Without recognition of these characters and appropriate handling, the index quality or indexer performance could degrade.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Unlike literate humans, computers do not understand the structure of a natural language document and cannot automatically recognize words and sentences.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] To a computer, a document is only a sequence of bytes.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Computers do not 'know' that a space character separates words in a document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Instead, humans must program the computer to identify what constitutes an individual or distinct word referred to as a token.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Such a program is commonly called a tokenizer or parser or lexer.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Many search engines, as well as other natural language processing software, incorporate specialized programs for parsing, such as YACC or Lex.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] During tokenization, the parser identifies sequences of characters that represent words and other elements, such as punctuation, which are represented by numeric codes, some of which are non-printing control characters.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The parser can also identify entities such as email addresses, phone numbers, and URLs.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] When identifying each token, several characteristics may be stored, such as the token's case (upper, lower, mixed, proper), language or encoding, lexical category (part of speech, like 'noun' or 'verb'), position, sentence number, sentence position, length, and line number.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine supports multiple languages, a common initial step during tokenization is to identify each document's language; many of the subsequent steps are language dependent (such as stemming and part of speech tagging).
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Language recognition is the process by which a computer program attempts to automatically identify, or categorize, the language of a document.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Other names for language recognition include language classification, language analysis, language identification, and language tagging.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Automated language recognition is the subject of ongoing research in natural language processing.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Finding which language the words belongs to may involve the use of a language recognition chart.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine supports multiple document formats, documents must be prepared for tokenization.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The challenge is that many document formats contain formatting information in addition to textual content.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For example, HTML documents contain HTML tags, which specify formatting information such as new line starts, bold emphasis, and font size or style.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine were to ignore the difference between content and 'markup', extraneous information would be included in the index, leading to poor search results.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis is the identification and handling of the formatting content embedded within documents which controls the way the document is rendered on a computer screen or interpreted by a software program.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis is also referred to as structure analysis, format parsing, tag stripping, format stripping, text normalization, text cleaning and text preparation.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The challenge of format analysis is further complicated by the intricacies of various file formats.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Certain file formats are proprietary with very little information disclosed, while others are well documented.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Options for dealing with various formats include using a publicly available commercial parsing tool that is offered by the organization which developed, maintains, or owns the format, and writing a custom parser.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Some search engines support inspection of files that are stored in a compressed or encrypted file format.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] When working with a compressed format, the indexer first decompresses the document; this step may result in one or more files, each of which must be indexed separately.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Format analysis can involve quality improvement methods to avoid including 'bad information' in the index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Content can manipulate the formatting information to include additional content.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Some search engines incorporate section recognition, the identification of major parts of a document, prior to tokenization.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Not all the documents in a corpus read like a well-written book, divided into organized chapters and pages.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Many documents on the web, such as newsletters and corporate reports, contain erroneous content and side-sections that do not contain primary material (that which the document is about).
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For example, articles on the Wikipedia website display a side menu with links to other web pages.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Some file formats, like HTML or PDF, allow for content to be displayed in columns.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Even though the content is displayed, or rendered, in different areas of the view, the raw markup content may store this information sequentially.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Words that appear sequentially in the raw source content are indexed sequentially, even though these sentences and paragraphs are rendered in different parts of the computer screen.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If search engines index this content as if it were normal content, the quality of the index and search quality may be degraded due to the mixed content and improper word proximity.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Section analysis may require the search engine to implement the rendering logic of each document, essentially an abstract representation of the actual document, and then index the representation instead.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For example, some content on the Internet is rendered via JavaScript.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] If the search engine does not render the page and evaluate the JavaScript within the page, it would not 'see' this content in the same way and would index the document incorrectly.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Given that some search engines do not bother with rendering issues, many web page designers avoid displaying content via JavaScript or use the Noscript Archived 2020-07-07 at the Wayback Machine tag to ensure that the web page is indexed properly.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] At the same time, this fact can also be exploited to cause the search engine indexer to 'see' different content than the viewer.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Indexing often has to recognize the HTML tags to organize priority.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Indexing low priority to high margin to labels like *strong* and *link* to optimize the order of priority if those labels are at the beginning of the text could not prove to be relevant.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Some indexers like Google and Bing ensure that the search engine does not take the large texts as relevant source due to strong type system compatibility.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Meta tag indexing plays an important role in organizing and categorizing web content.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Specific documents often contain embedded meta information such as author, keywords, description, and language.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] For HTML pages, the meta tag contains keywords which are also included in the index.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Earlier Internet search engine technology would only index the keywords in the meta tags for the forward index; the full document would not be parsed.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] At that time full-text indexing was not as well established, nor was computer hardware able to support such technology.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The design of the HTML markup language initially included support for meta tags for the very purpose of being properly and easily indexed, without requiring tokenization.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] As the Internet grew through the 1990s, many brick-and-mortar corporations went 'online' and established corporate websites.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The keywords used to describe webpages (many of which were corporate-oriented webpages similar to product brochures) changed from descriptive to marketing-oriented keywords designed to drive sales by placing the webpage high in the search results for specific search queries.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] The fact that these keywords were subjectively specified was leading to spamdexing, which drove many search engines to adopt full-text indexing technologies in the 1990s.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Search engine designers and companies could only place so many 'marketing keywords' into the content of a webpage before draining it of all interesting and useful information.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Given that conflict of interest with the business goal of designing user-oriented websites which were 'sticky', the customer lifetime value equation was changed to incorporate more useful content into the website in hopes of retaining the visitor.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In this sense, full-text indexing was more objective and increased the quality of search engine results, as it was one more step away from subjective control of search engine result placement, which in turn furthered research of full-text indexing technologies.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] In desktop search, many solutions incorporate meta tags to provide a way for authors to further customize how the search engine will index content from various files that is not evident from the file content.
[src:apache-solr/search-engine-indexing] Desktop search is more under the control of the user, while Internet search engines must focus more on the full text index.
